  "signature": "ed25519:b2d4f6a8c0e2b4d6f8a0c2e4b6d8f0a2c4e6b8d0f2a4c6e8b0d2f4a6c8e0b2d4",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/sqa-level2",
      "rationale": "All three FEA codes (FDA in-house, Ansys 2023 R1, DePuy Synthes internal) are operated under documented software quality assurance plans conforming to FDA 21 CFR Part 11 and ISO 9001. Version-controlled input decks, automated regression test suites, and signed release notes are maintained. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects formal SQA plans with independent audit trail; required Gradation 2 for Medium model risk is met with margin."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/code-verification-level2",
      "rationale": "Each FEA code was verified against NAFEMS benchmark problems LE1 and LE10 and against analytical solutions for Euler-Bernoulli beam bending and Hertzian contact. Convergence of the verification benchmarks to within 0.5% of reference values was confirmed. Ansys and FDA codes additionally passed ASME V&V 10 standard benchmark suite. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects multi-benchmark, documented verification with quantified residuals."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/discretization-error-level2",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh convergence study was conducted using three mesh refinement levels (coarse ~180k elements, medium ~520k elements, fine ~1.4M elements). Richardson extrapolation yielded a Grid Convergence Index (GCI) of 0.8% for stiffness and 1.1% for yield force at the medium mesh density selected for production runs. Discretization error is bounded and documented; achieved Gradation 3 reflects formal GCI analysis per Roache methodology."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/solver-error-level1",
      "rationale": "Static implicit nonlinear solver with Newton-Raphson iteration was used. Force and displacement residual convergence tolerances set to 1×10⁻⁴ (relative). Solver residual histories were archived and reviewed for all 11 simulation runs; no convergence failures or spurious oscillations were observed. Contact stabilization energy was monitored and confirmed below 0.1% of total strain energy. Achieved Gradation 2 reflects documented residual monitoring with quantified tolerances."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/use-error-level2",
      "rationale": "A documented simulation protocol with step-by-step pre-processing, boundary condition application, and post-processing checklists was followed by all three analyst teams. Independent peer review of input decks was performed by a second analyst at each site. Boundary condition definitions (fixed inferior vertebral body, applied displacement at superior loading fixture) were cross-checked against ASTM F1717 standard and test fixture drawings. No discrepancies were found across the three independent model instantiations."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/model-form-level2",
      "rationale": "The FEA model employs a nonlinear isotropic hardening plasticity constitutive law for Ti-6Al-4V screw material, validated against coupon tensile test data from the same material lot used in bench specimens. Cortical bone analogue (UHMWPE block) is modeled as linear elastic with modulus measured from compression testing of the same material lot. Frictional contact (μ=0.2) between screw-rod interface is consistent with published tribological data for Ti-Ti contact in saline. Model form choices are physically motivated and documented."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/model-inputs-level2",
      "rationale": "All material property inputs (Young's modulus, yield stress, tangent modulus for Ti-6Al-4V; modulus for UHMWPE block) were measured from the same material lots used in bench testing. Geometric inputs were derived from calibrated CMM measurements of actual test specimens (n=3 screws, n=3 rods measured). Dimensional variability was characterized and propagated through a Monte Carlo sensitivity analysis (1000 samples); QoI variability attributable to geometry was ±1.8%, well within acceptance bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/test-samples-level2",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories (Lab 1: n=6, Lab 2: n=5). All constructs were assembled from the same production lot of screws and rods. Dimensional inspection of each construct was performed pre-test via CMM. Material certificates of conformance were obtained for all components. Inter-laboratory variability was characterized (CV=3.2% for stiffness, CV=4.1% for yield force), confirming reproducibility."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/test-conditions-level2",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single prescribed loading condition per ASTM F1717 (static compression-bending at 5 mm/min crosshead displacement). While the standard protocol was followed rigorously with calibrated load cells (NIST-traceable, ±0.5% accuracy) and environmental control (23±2°C, ambient humidity), only one loading rate and one loading angle were investigated. This limitation means Gradation 2 is achieved rather than the required Gradation 3. This known shortfall is acknowledged in the overall credibility assessment and is offset by the strength of the other 12 factors, all of which meet or exceed their required levels. The decision authority accepted this gap given the regulatory precedent of ASTM F1717 as a standardized single-condition test."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/equivalency-inputs-level2",
      "rationale": "A formal equivalency mapping table was constructed linking each FEA model input parameter to its experimental counterpart measurement. Material properties (E, σ_y, E_tan) were mapped to coupon test results from the same lot. Geometric parameters were mapped to CMM measurements of the same constructs. Boundary conditions were mapped to test fixture drawings and load cell calibration records. All 14 input parameters were confirmed equivalent within their respective measurement uncertainties. No surrogate or assumed values were required."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/output-comparison-level2",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs were compared: construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement. For each QoI, the normalized model error E = (FEA − Experiment)/Experiment was computed, and the validation metric E/uval was evaluated against the ±1.96 criterion. Results: stiffness E/uval=0.87, yield force E/uval=1.12, force at 40 mm E/uval=1.03. All three QoIs pass the acceptance criterion. Additionally, full load-displacement curve overlay plots were generated and archived, showing excellent morphological agreement including the post-yield softening region."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/qoi-relevance-level2",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly specified in ASTM F1717 as the required performance metrics for pedicle screw construct evaluation. These QoIs are mechanistically linked to the clinical failure modes of interest (construct loosening from sub-yield cyclic loading, acute fracture at yield, and large-deformation failure). The mapping from QoI to clinical consequence was documented in the risk analysis and reviewed by the clinical advisor. No surrogate or proxy QoIs were required."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/validation-relevance-level2",
      "rationale": "The validation activity is directly coincident with the COU: the same FEA model ensemble, the same non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw geometry, the same ASTM F1717 test configuration, and the same three QoIs used in the regulatory submission. There is no extrapolation from a surrogate geometry or loading condition. The validation domain fully encloses the intended use domain. This represents the highest achievable relevance for a device-specific validation study and justifies Gradation 3 for this factor."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-noncannulated-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/actor/credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (Non-cannulated pedicle screw compression-bending FEA) is accepted at Medium assurance level. Of the 13 ASME V&V 40 factors evaluated, 12 meet or exceed their required credibility levels. The single exception is Test Conditions (achieved Gradation 2 vs. required Gradation 3), which reflects the inherent constraint of the ASTM F1717 standard protocol specifying a single loading condition. This shortfall was explicitly acknowledged and accepted by the decision authority on the following grounds: (1) ASTM F1717 is a recognized FDA-accepted consensus standard for this device class, and regulatory precedent establishes the single-condition test as sufficient for 510(k) clearance; (2) the remaining 12 factors all achieve their required levels, providing substantial compensating evidence; (3) all three QoIs (stiffness E/uval=0.87, yield force E/uval=1.12, force at 40 mm E/uval=1.03) pass the pre-specified ±1.96 validation metric, demonstrating quantitative agreement between FEA and experiment within combined model and experimental uncertainty; (4) the model risk level of 3 (Medium) is consistent with the Medium assurance level targeted; and (5) the provenance chain from raw experimental measurements through uncertainty quantification to validation results is complete and traceable. The overall weight of evidence supports the conclusion that the FEA modeling framework is credible for its intended use in the regulatory submission for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
